[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, it's honestly, it will probably end up taking quite a bit longer than the sort of equivalent underpass on the other side, which was built by private development, which can go faster and they kind of, it's not to say that's not as good, but it just, you know, they don't have the same risk.

557
00:47:13,762 --> 00:47:17,285
[SPEAKER_00]: Like, constraints as a state funded project with regard to the tip.

558
00:47:17,325 --> 00:47:21,428
[SPEAKER_10]: I know that's 1 of the mailing lists that I'm on and I periodically get paying that says.

559
00:47:22,309 --> 00:47:25,852
[SPEAKER_10]: Comment period open for the and it's always something absurd.

560
00:47:25,892 --> 00:47:26,993
[SPEAKER_10]: It's like the 2026 tip.

561
00:47:30,083 --> 00:47:36,266
[SPEAKER_10]: It's like these things are really far in the future from our standpoint.

562
00:47:36,366 --> 00:47:43,870
[SPEAKER_10]: It makes sense because everyone has a plan for it, but it's not like money is put into the tip for something that's going to happen this fall.

563
00:47:44,430 --> 00:47:49,152
[SPEAKER_10]: It's like the tip lines are things that are really pretty far in the future.

564
00:47:49,172 --> 00:47:52,253
[SPEAKER_10]: They're hard to track down too, I found.

565
00:47:52,273 --> 00:47:53,174
[SPEAKER_10]: They're really hard.

566
00:47:53,214 --> 00:47:57,496
[SPEAKER_10]: You got to sort them in just the right way to find the project in question.

567
00:47:58,400 --> 00:48:05,240
[SPEAKER_10]: You know, and it might not even end up being in the community you think it's in because of some weird, you know, the way it's allocated.

568
00:48:07,522 --> 00:48:08,503
[SPEAKER_00]: Right now, I totally agree.

569
00:48:08,523 --> 00:48:10,384
[SPEAKER_00]: It's not that user friendly.

570
00:48:10,404 --> 00:48:22,014
[SPEAKER_00]: So I think 1 of the things the city is trying to do is to kind of extract the useful stuff in the meetings and anything that we think would be a little easier for the public to connect with and try to publicize that.

571
00:48:22,074 --> 00:48:29,580
[SPEAKER_00]: It just so happens that for the underpass, we don't really have anything new since the design public hearing stuff that happened almost a year ago.

572
00:48:29,680 --> 00:48:34,865
[SPEAKER_00]: So we'll hopefully have something in the next couple of months that we can at least share with people.

573
00:48:35,406 --> 00:48:36,070
[SPEAKER_09]: Cool.

574
00:48:36,271 --> 00:48:38,446
[SPEAKER_09]: People are interested and ready for a picture.

575
00:48:39,495 --> 00:48:55,705
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, and on a related note, there's another project along that in that same area, the extension of the Wellington Greenway, which has just been put on the tip and we're now just starting the process to get we have a project manager with MassDOT.

576
00:48:56,185 --> 00:49:03,530
[SPEAKER_00]: We're getting the preliminary stuff ready to kind of get an existing design into MassDOT's hands.

577
00:49:03,610 --> 00:49:08,313
[SPEAKER_00]: So you will hear more about that project soon, but it's in a much earlier stage.

578
00:49:09,545 --> 00:49:16,832
[SPEAKER_11]: The other thing I would add is that it's usually a few years between 100% design and construction.

579
00:49:18,093 --> 00:49:20,955
[SPEAKER_11]: Very true, yeah.

580
00:49:20,975 --> 00:49:25,640
[SPEAKER_11]: The 100% design for the Clippership Connector was in October of 2020.

581
00:49:28,122 --> 00:49:33,046
[SPEAKER_11]: And construction might start this fall, so three years.

582
00:49:36,520 --> 00:49:40,441
[SPEAKER_11]: And that's just sort of typical project timelines.

583
00:49:40,621 --> 00:49:44,142
[SPEAKER_11]: Like once they have the design, it takes them a while to put it out to bid.

584
00:49:44,702 --> 00:49:46,902
[SPEAKER_11]: Then it takes them a while to look at the bids.

585
00:49:47,443 --> 00:49:56,625
[SPEAKER_11]: Then, you know, once they select a bid, then it takes the bid winner a while to start, like a year sometimes.

586
00:49:57,285 --> 00:49:59,165
[SPEAKER_11]: So there's just.

587
00:50:01,686 --> 00:50:04,327
[SPEAKER_11]: It's in terms in terms of outreach, at least.

588
00:50:07,328 --> 00:50:10,550
[SPEAKER_11]: people often want to know, when is this thing going to actually happen?

589
00:50:12,231 --> 00:50:17,175
[SPEAKER_11]: And unfortunately, the answer is usually not that soon.

590
00:50:20,797 --> 00:50:34,541
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah, I mean, so even just expectations management, I think I went back for the Wellington Post that I had done and said, 100% design is a year from now.

591
00:50:35,261 --> 00:50:39,402
[SPEAKER_09]: And that's why, and then it has to go out to bid and then construction is in 2025.

592
00:50:40,202 --> 00:50:43,343
[SPEAKER_09]: I tried to give people- Yeah, that's the thing.

593
00:50:44,043 --> 00:50:45,524
[SPEAKER_11]: They will say things like that.

594
00:50:47,493 --> 00:50:55,420
[SPEAKER_11]: They will say that, you know, they're going to have 100% design in a certain time and then they'll construct construction right after that.

595
00:50:56,581 --> 00:50:59,664
[SPEAKER_11]: That never pans out in reality.

596
00:50:59,684 --> 00:51:04,188
[SPEAKER_11]: Because they said they were going to start super super connected construction like two years ago.

597
00:51:05,850 --> 00:51:06,731
[SPEAKER_11]: That did not happen.

598
