01:05:46,650 --> 01:05:50,393
[SPEAKER_00]: So anytime a private developer wants to put a bike rack on their property or whatever.

722
01:05:51,294 --> 01:05:52,915
[SPEAKER_00]: We say, please look at this.

723
01:05:53,115 --> 01:05:53,895
[SPEAKER_00]: Here's the specs.

724
01:05:54,096 --> 01:05:55,216
[SPEAKER_00]: Here's what kind of racks you want.

725
01:05:55,256 --> 01:06:02,760
[SPEAKER_00]: Here's what you don't want, because we really do want to make sure we're not having these bad, not useful ones kind of popping up.

726
01:06:03,261 --> 01:06:05,842
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm going to try to find the guide so I can kind of link it.

727
01:06:05,882 --> 01:06:07,383
[SPEAKER_00]: It's really short and simple.

728
01:06:07,443 --> 01:06:14,487
[SPEAKER_00]: And so basically, any time we get that situation, we point them to this guide, which I think is useful.

729
01:06:14,527 --> 01:06:17,328
[SPEAKER_00]: Because I agree there's no real need to reinvent the wheel.

730
01:06:18,889 --> 01:06:20,390
[SPEAKER_00]: There's already really good standards out there.

731
01:06:20,785 --> 01:06:32,535
[SPEAKER_09]: Right, and I think the other thing is, I think I would rather have a call sooner with the store manager or target that just says, guidelines exist, demands exist.

732
01:06:33,056 --> 01:06:34,517
[SPEAKER_09]: We're just an advisory commission.

733
01:06:34,577 --> 01:06:40,602
[SPEAKER_09]: We can just tell you that the demand is there, and here's a good way to meet it.

734
01:06:41,563 --> 01:06:51,810
[SPEAKER_09]: And then, you know, we'd have to see how far we get, you know, whether one out of every 10 people that we talk to in that way ultimately installs a rack.

735
01:06:52,650 --> 01:06:55,692
[SPEAKER_09]: I would still have to, I'd still take credit for those.

736
01:06:57,453 --> 01:07:02,757
[SPEAKER_09]: And then we can figure out later what we have to do to boost our response rate and effectiveness.

737
01:07:04,298 --> 01:07:06,099
[SPEAKER_09]: But I'd rather get started sooner.

738
01:07:09,226 --> 01:07:34,612
[SPEAKER_09]: Even with, the picture in the post that I shared was actually from one of the middle schools where the rack that they had was pretty crappy and pretty full and had a gap next to it where you could put, even if it was just another crappy rack, it would, you know, it seemed like it had the prospect of actually getting used, particularly on walk and bike to school day.

739
01:07:36,612 --> 01:07:38,553
[SPEAKER_09]: Right where are those bikes gonna park when they get there?

740
01:07:39,233 --> 01:07:59,845
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah, I'm not suggesting that we let the perfection be the enemy of the good here and making this into a multi-year technical advisory project, but we should at least, as Lillian has already said, apparently we can provide technical pointers and

741
01:08:00,645 --> 01:08:09,692
[SPEAKER_08]: a quasi-advisory role in helping people, private people, spend their money wisely and get this done.

742
01:08:10,193 --> 01:08:22,462
[SPEAKER_08]: So it's just a matter of maybe, as you say, getting to it and starting it on a, as the demand requires, on a first-come, first-served basis.

743
01:08:23,203 --> 01:08:27,046
[SPEAKER_08]: So I think we're all in agreement here that we can go forward with this.

744
01:08:28,047 --> 01:08:33,611
[SPEAKER_08]: But I just want us to be clear as to how our involvement is carved out.

745
01:08:34,471 --> 01:08:50,703
[SPEAKER_08]: And so there is no private versus public friction for, you know, payment systems or, but, you know, uniformity of design and safety and all that, you know, should have some technical governance.

746
01:08:51,303 --> 01:08:53,825
[SPEAKER_08]: And Lillian is suggesting that's already there.

747
01:08:54,325 --> 01:08:55,366
[SPEAKER_08]: So, great.

748
01:08:59,179 --> 01:09:09,454
[SPEAKER_00]: I do want to jump in on the public side with good news that the city was awarded a grant from the MPO to install 40 bike racks on public sidewalks.

749
01:09:10,095 --> 01:09:13,259
[SPEAKER_00]: According to the map that you guys generated, which was.

750
01:09:13,680 --> 01:09:15,321
[SPEAKER_00]: I don't know, a year ago at this point.

751
01:09:15,381 --> 01:09:17,062
[SPEAKER_00]: It was a while ago.

752
01:09:17,182 --> 01:09:18,383
[SPEAKER_00]: So that is happening.

753
01:09:18,423 --> 01:09:28,229
[SPEAKER_00]: And the exciting thing about it is that the grant also covers the installation costs for the city to hire a contractor to do this, which I know there's pros and cons to that sort of conceptually.

754
01:09:28,249 --> 01:09:30,630
[SPEAKER_00]: But in practice, that means we don't have to wait.

755
01:09:30,730 --> 01:09:32,692
[SPEAKER_00]: Our DPW is pretty overloaded.

756
01:09:32,812 --> 01:09:39,356
[SPEAKER_00]: So the fact that we can hire a company to do this will mean we don't have to rely on DPW's capacity to get that done.

757
01:09:40,176 --> 01:09:47,759
[SPEAKER_00]: Not sure on the timeline of when we're going to be able to actually get the contract out and try to find somebody to do this, but the grant has been awarded.

758
01:09:47,859 --> 01:09:51,861
[SPEAKER_00]: So at least there were kind of getting a step in the right direction.

759
01:09:54,162 --> 01:10:01,645
[SPEAKER_09]: Would it be useful for me to republicize the old map or the existing map and and and get feedback on it?

760
01:10:03,113 --> 01:10:06,094
[SPEAKER_09]: Um, and let me know when we can.

761
01:10:07,095 --> 01:10:14,858
[SPEAKER_00]: Possibly, if you wouldn't mind holding off on that, particularly for a social media post, just because I think there's, I think the city wants to do an announcement.

762
01:10:14,878 --> 01:10:17,399
[SPEAKER_00]: There was a couple other elements of this grant too.

763
01:10:18,159 --> 01:10:20,660
[SPEAKER_00]: So, they may want to do their own announcement about it.

764
01:10:20,980 --> 01:10:21,140
[SPEAKER_00]: Um.

765
01:10:21,540 --> 01:10:28,363
[SPEAKER_00]: But I wanted to share it with you guys that you wouldn't have to wait because this is something you've talked about since for a while and last meeting extensively.

766
01:10:28,443 --> 01:10:28,563
[SPEAKER_00]: So.

767
01:10:29,423 --> 01:10:32,725
[SPEAKER_00]: Um, but I will keep you guys posted on the progress on that front.

768
01:10:32,785 --> 01:10:45,774
[SPEAKER_00]: And once it's, you know, once we can start publicizing it, we can certainly share around the map again and kind of perhaps 1 of the things to do is to start collecting additional locations, given that the 40 that have already been chosen.

769
01:10:45,794 --> 01:10:49,116
[SPEAKER_00]: Are now planned for, you know, maybe a 2nd round.

770
01:10:49,976 --> 01:10:53,679
[SPEAKER_00]: Starting the thinking process for that could be useful in anticipation of future grants.

771
01:10:54,289 --> 01:10:55,109
[SPEAKER_11]: We did more than 40.

772
01:10:55,630 --> 01:11:02,853
[SPEAKER_11]: In that in the last round, we divided them up into phases, but I think you're right.

773
01:11:02,953 --> 01:11:04,874
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, I think that sounds familiar.

774
01:11:05,855 --> 01:11:06,355
[SPEAKER_11]: 75 or something.

775
01:11:06,375 --> 01:11:12,618
[SPEAKER_11]: I don't remember exactly, but it was like tier one, tier two, tier three kind of things, but there were a bunch.

776
01:11:14,259 --> 01:11:17,200
[SPEAKER_15]: So sorry, I think I only have the tier one map, but.

777
01:11:17,340 --> 01:11:19,922
[SPEAKER_15]: What was the the quantity of bike racks?

778
01:11:21,227 --> 01:11:26,669
[SPEAKER_00]: 40 racks, which I believe was tier was the tier one that be Dan is referring to.

779
01:11:26,689 --> 01:11:29,230
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah, or maybe I'll have to go.

780
01:11:29,250 --> 01:11:32,811
[SPEAKER_00]: I don't know if I have a map of tier two, but I know that Amy mentioned it to me before.

781
01:11:32,831 --> 01:11:35,511
[SPEAKER_09]: 40 sounds amazing to me.

782
01:11:36,352 --> 01:11:37,232
[SPEAKER_00]: It's definitely a start.

783
01:11:39,773 --> 01:11:41,193
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah, I mean, I was kind of doing it's awesome.

784
01:11:41,313 --> 01:11:44,054
[SPEAKER_09]: I got five squares and two shopping malls, seven.

785
01:11:44,274 --> 01:11:47,035
[SPEAKER_09]: That was kind of the number I was walking around with.

786
01:11:49,875 --> 01:11:51,416
[SPEAKER_15]: Well, congratulations.

787
01:11:51,436 --> 01:11:52,637
[SPEAKER_15]: That's very, very exciting.

788
01:11:52,817 --> 01:11:55,178
[SPEAKER_15]: Very happy to get that money for the racks.

789
01:11:55,258 --> 01:11:57,920
[SPEAKER_15]: And I think we know where to put them, which is everywhere.

790
01:12:01,242 --> 01:12:01,962
[SPEAKER_08]: Let me be clear.

791
01:12:02,002 --> 01:12:05,244
[SPEAKER_08]: Is that 40 bicycles or 40 actual racks?

792
01:12:06,305 --> 01:12:08,026
[SPEAKER_00]: 40 racks.

793
01:12:08,106 --> 01:12:11,548
[SPEAKER_00]: I think most of the racks are single staples.

794
01:12:11,608 --> 01:12:15,630
[SPEAKER_00]: I think maybe a couple of them are like two

795
01:12:17,131 --> 01:12:40,407
[SPEAKER_11]: Yeah, I'm like I could probably pick up the actual map, but like that was most of our recommendations just to get well to get a sort of wide distribution for one thing, because it's just a lot of the spots are just like on sidewalks, but also most of the spots that we could think of to put larger racks were on private property.

796
01:12:42,420 --> 01:12:44,661
[SPEAKER_11]: That, you know, there's lots of places, you know, like a target.

797
01:12:44,781 --> 01:12:44,981
[SPEAKER_11]: Yeah.

798
01:12:45,281 --> 01:12:49,983
[SPEAKER_11]: Could, could use a multi bike rack there.

799
01:12:50,003 --> 01:12:58,307
[SPEAKER_11]: It would be great, but we were only looking at places that, you know, the city had public property, um, that we could put stuff.

800
01:12:58,627 --> 01:13:00,328
[SPEAKER_11]: So we didn't include those.

801
01:13:00,368 --> 01:13:10,892
[SPEAKER_11]: Like if we can reach out to business owners, whatever, who have space and demand, um, and get them to install stuff, that would also be a great.

802
01:13:15,242 --> 01:13:24,144
[SPEAKER_08]: So we're at least saying we have, with those 40, we may have the capacity for 60 or 70 bikes.

803
01:13:24,944 --> 01:13:25,824
[SPEAKER_11]: Something like that.

804
01:13:26,485 --> 01:13:26,805
[SPEAKER_08]: At least 80.

805
01:13:26,925 --> 01:13:27,805
[SPEAKER_11]: At least 80.

806
01:13:27,845 --> 01:13:28,905
[SPEAKER_11]: Okay.

807
01:13:29,025 --> 01:13:30,926
[SPEAKER_11]: Every staple can hold at least two bikes.

808
01:13:30,946 --> 01:13:36,567
[SPEAKER_11]: There were a couple of places where we thought, you know, could use a double staple or, you know, something else like that.

809
01:13:37,538 --> 01:13:45,141
[SPEAKER_08]: but the publicly installed ones are apt to be one to two to three like capacity, not six or 10.

810
01:13:45,802 --> 01:13:47,442
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay.

811
01:13:47,943 --> 01:13:49,263
[SPEAKER_08]: Just helpful to know.

812
01:13:49,663 --> 01:13:56,967
[SPEAKER_09]: They are errand oriented locations, not, you know, I'm filling an auditorium with cyclists.

813
01:13:57,427 --> 01:14:00,028
[SPEAKER_08]: Not stations, but really parking spaces.

814
01:14:00,328 --> 01:14:00,568
[SPEAKER_08]: Right.

815
01:14:02,329 --> 01:14:04,150
[SPEAKER_08]: To use that parlance.

816
01:14:10,918 --> 01:14:20,783
[SPEAKER_16]: I think that might cover most of our stuff on bike racks and just in time to move over to the tentative and back organized events.

817
01:14:21,483 --> 01:14:29,327
[SPEAKER_16]: I know that Leah, who she said she couldn't be here tonight but she had brought up the idea of a Halloween bike parade.

818
01:14:30,517 --> 01:14:35,341
[SPEAKER_16]: I think that's actually an interesting idea.

819
01:14:35,461 --> 01:14:40,084
[SPEAKER_16]: I'm not sure what other events might be going on with the city around Halloween.

820
01:14:40,144 --> 01:14:43,466
[SPEAKER_16]: Is anyone else more plugged into that?

821
01:14:44,987 --> 01:14:52,072
[SPEAKER_01]: I know the squares all do their little kid trick-or-treating on the same evening.

822
01:14:52,313 --> 01:14:58,737
[SPEAKER_01]: West Medford and Medford Square both do whatever, trick-or-treating at the businesses.

823
01:15:03,180 --> 01:15:11,187
[SPEAKER_01]: I mean, I was gonna say it could be a great time to do something like that because the streets are already just like inundated with children.

824
01:15:11,388 --> 01:15:15,592
[SPEAKER_01]: There's already police officers that are stationed to help people cross.

825
01:15:16,433 --> 01:15:19,656
[SPEAKER_01]: I know we do the West Medford one, so like crossing at High Street.

826
01:15:22,679 --> 01:15:23,700
[SPEAKER_01]: But it's also at like,

827
01:15:25,170 --> 01:15:30,054
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't know what day Halloween is on, but last year was at like five o'clock on a Friday.

828
01:15:30,194 --> 01:15:37,059
[SPEAKER_01]: And so like so much backed up traffic because of the Halloween events.

829
01:15:37,279 --> 01:15:41,382
[SPEAKER_01]: So I don't know how they feel about adding bikes in that sense.

830
01:15:41,602 --> 01:15:41,822
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

831
01:15:42,443 --> 01:15:43,524
[SPEAKER_08]: It's a Tuesday this year.

832
01:15:44,484 --> 01:15:44,825
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay.

833
01:15:45,025 --> 01:15:47,987
[SPEAKER_01]: So yeah, I mean, they might still just do it always like the Friday before.

834
01:15:48,007 --> 01:15:50,169
[SPEAKER_01]: I could see that thing.

835
01:15:50,789 --> 01:15:51,790
[SPEAKER_01]: I haven't looked it up yet.

836
01:15:53,541 --> 01:15:54,402
[SPEAKER_15]: That sounds right.

837
01:15:54,442 --> 01:15:58,224
[SPEAKER_15]: I think the square does something on like the Friday before, if I'm not mistaken.

838
01:15:59,985 --> 01:16:02,846
[SPEAKER_01]: But I mean, it sounds fun.

839
01:16:02,866 --> 01:16:07,569
[SPEAKER_01]: I would love to see kids on bikes and their stands.

840
01:16:09,750 --> 01:16:16,234
[SPEAKER_15]: Yeah, I mean, that's, that's something I don't feel like we've ever really gotten into that sort of thing, like leading a lot of

841
01:16:17,769 --> 01:16:19,770
[SPEAKER_15]: kind of festive bike ride type things.

842
01:16:19,850 --> 01:16:20,851
[SPEAKER_15]: I like the idea of it.

843
01:16:20,871 --> 01:16:25,514
[SPEAKER_15]: They tend to be very well, if they're well organized, they tend to be very well attended.

844
01:16:25,534 --> 01:16:29,376
[SPEAKER_15]: Like I know there's quite a few of those in Somerville and whatnot that are really popular.

845
01:16:29,416 --> 01:16:34,519
[SPEAKER_15]: Like the, what is it, the jingle ride or whichever one goes out looking at holiday lights.

846
01:16:34,559 --> 01:16:37,301
[SPEAKER_15]: You know, that's hundreds of people go out, including kids.

847
01:16:37,321 --> 01:16:38,462
[SPEAKER_01]: The Halloween one's coming up.

848
01:16:38,742 --> 01:16:39,382
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm going to it.

849
01:16:39,662 --> 01:16:40,143
[SPEAKER_01]: It's fun.

850
01:16:41,403 --> 01:16:42,564
[SPEAKER_15]: Yeah.

851
01:16:42,624 --> 01:16:43,905
[SPEAKER_15]: What do they do for that one, Mary Kate?

852
01:16:44,465 --> 01:16:48,828
[SPEAKER_01]: They're starting at Magnolia Park and they, I forget where they're ending.

853
01:16:51,950 --> 01:17:04,777
[SPEAKER_01]: And I went last year, it was a different route, but like everybody gathers and kind of parks their bikes in a line or like a U and the kids can just run from bike to bike and do their trick or treating.

854
01:17:04,817 --> 01:17:13,243
[SPEAKER_01]: So you bring candy to pass out and then we get on the bikes and bike to the next playground.

855
01:17:14,388 --> 01:17:15,648
[SPEAKER_01]: all of us in costume.

856
01:17:17,049 --> 01:17:21,470
[SPEAKER_01]: And yeah, mostly along like a lot of times like Somerville Community Path.

857
01:17:21,550 --> 01:17:30,032
[SPEAKER_01]: And they do a good job of, yeah, having crossing guards stations.

858
01:17:30,092 --> 01:17:32,873
[SPEAKER_01]: Sometimes it's like state representatives and stuff.

859
01:17:32,953 --> 01:17:38,655
[SPEAKER_01]: And sometimes it's just normal people like me who would help.

860
01:17:38,835 --> 01:17:42,536
[SPEAKER_01]: But they do a good job of keeping it safe and organized.

861
01:17:43,593 --> 01:18:02,768
[SPEAKER_08]: I have to wonder if having kids unhelmeted, sometimes wearing headgear that tunnels their vision, when wearing costumes, should be pedaling on bicycles, are two things that are completely contradictory.

862
01:18:04,470 --> 01:18:06,971
[SPEAKER_08]: I mean, really, and genuinely unsafe.

863
01:18:07,472 --> 01:18:21,299
[SPEAKER_08]: And certainly, if Cinderella and, you know, Eric the mongol is out there, they're not going to be wearing their little Schwinn helmets asking for trick-or-treats while rolling along on a bicycle.

864
01:18:21,319 --> 01:18:22,680
[SPEAKER_08]: It's just not going to happen.

865
01:18:22,700 --> 01:18:24,440
[SPEAKER_08]: I don't see it as safe at all.

866
01:18:24,460 --> 01:18:33,005
[SPEAKER_08]: A rolling bicycle doing trick-or-treating in odd gear is not about bicycling.

867
01:18:34,466 --> 01:18:36,348
[SPEAKER_08]: So help me with that.

868
01:18:36,368 --> 01:18:38,970
[SPEAKER_08]: I don't know how to put those two activities together.

869
01:18:39,811 --> 01:18:47,738
[SPEAKER_10]: Well, I think it's probably illegal, too, if you're thinking about it, because if you're riding a bike and you're under the age of 15, you're supposed to have a helmet on, right?

870
01:18:48,279 --> 01:18:48,539
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah.

871
01:18:49,380 --> 01:18:51,342
[SPEAKER_08]: Well, I mean, even if you're a wizard.

872
01:18:53,107 --> 01:19:01,254
[SPEAKER_01]: You could make it part of the requirement, I guess, to be a part of, like, the bike parade and have, like, clear messaging around helmets are required.

873
01:19:02,214 --> 01:19:15,885
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't think the vision was to have kids, like, biking to, like, from, like, business to business, but having maybe, like, a parade, I don't know, that would kick off the event, you know?

874
01:19:17,226 --> 01:19:21,690
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't have any experience doing such an event, nor do I have

875
01:19:23,207 --> 01:19:28,655
[SPEAKER_01]: Experience on what it would be like if we tried to enforce that you have to wear a helmet on the bike parade.

876
01:19:29,396 --> 01:19:32,901
[SPEAKER_10]: Suggest that the kids would ride from park to park and then.

877
01:19:34,203 --> 01:19:36,907
[SPEAKER_10]: Basically, the Halloween event would be at the park.

878
01:19:39,054 --> 01:19:40,696
[SPEAKER_01]: That's an event that already exists.

879
01:19:40,996 --> 01:19:44,959
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm going to it on September 22nd with my kids.

880
01:19:45,019 --> 01:19:47,721
[SPEAKER_01]: I went to the same event last year.

881
01:19:47,761 --> 01:19:51,064
[SPEAKER_01]: It was a different bike route last year, but they hold this event.

882
01:19:52,365 --> 01:20:01,333
[SPEAKER_10]: That would work where you helmet up, you ride to the next park, you drop your bike, and you change into your costume, you do your thing at the park, and then you go to another park.

883
01:20:01,713 --> 01:20:02,814
[SPEAKER_10]: Same thing.

884
01:20:02,834 --> 01:20:06,497
[SPEAKER_10]: I don't know how well that would work, but that's something I could envision, I suppose.

885
01:20:09,105 --> 01:20:13,108
[SPEAKER_08]: Did your kids wear helmets while they were doing this last year?

886
01:20:13,768 --> 01:20:16,490
[SPEAKER_01]: I have a cargo bike, so they ride on the back.

887
01:20:16,510 --> 01:20:19,111
[SPEAKER_01]: But yes, my kids always wear helmets.

888
01:20:19,472 --> 01:20:21,313
[SPEAKER_01]: And my daughter hates it.

889
01:20:21,353 --> 01:20:22,734
[SPEAKER_01]: I make her wear reflective vests.

890
01:20:22,894 --> 01:20:24,575
[SPEAKER_01]: And I put the big flag on her bike.

891
01:20:24,655 --> 01:20:26,476
[SPEAKER_01]: And she's like, this flag is stupid.

892
01:20:26,616 --> 01:20:29,398
[SPEAKER_08]: And it still ends up being sufficient.

893
01:20:29,458 --> 01:20:30,699
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm obsessed with safety.

894
01:20:32,440 --> 01:20:37,223
[SPEAKER_08]: But it ends up being sufficiently Halloween-y for them and their enjoyment.

895
01:20:38,368 --> 01:20:38,828
[SPEAKER_01]: Oh, yeah.

896
01:20:38,948 --> 01:20:42,611
[SPEAKER_01]: I mean, they're like I said, they're not for these events.

897
01:20:42,711 --> 01:20:44,632
[SPEAKER_01]: I just put them on the back of my cargo bike.

898
01:20:44,792 --> 01:20:47,634
[SPEAKER_01]: And so they don't have to pedal, but they do wear their helmets.

899
01:20:48,434 --> 01:20:48,594
[SPEAKER_01]: And

