01:37:31,936 --> 01:37:39,613
[SPEAKER_08]: Well, when you mention a brewery or a brew hall, I just wonder if that's one of the criteria for us to hold an event there.

1081
01:37:40,349 --> 01:37:42,510
[SPEAKER_08]: is that it falls within completely.

1082
01:37:42,530 --> 01:37:51,272
[SPEAKER_10]: I would think any location that we hold an event that would be the case, and I would be surprised if such a venue is not inherently accessible as necessary.

1083
01:37:52,913 --> 01:38:02,316
[SPEAKER_10]: I just can't imagine that at this point any new business is going to be able to get their license, occupancy license, without that kind of access.

1084
01:38:02,797 --> 01:38:04,599
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah, pretty much for a new building.

1085
01:38:05,119 --> 01:38:07,181
[SPEAKER_08]: Should it be required to have a bike rack?

1086
01:38:07,621 --> 01:38:08,082
[SPEAKER_08]: Never mind.

1087
01:38:08,242 --> 01:38:08,982
[SPEAKER_08]: Maybe that's not.

1088
01:38:09,283 --> 01:38:09,923
[SPEAKER_08]: Of course not.

1089
01:38:10,243 --> 01:38:11,745
[SPEAKER_10]: There's no law regarding that.

1090
01:38:12,245 --> 01:38:13,746
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm just kidding.

1091
01:38:13,947 --> 01:38:14,387
[SPEAKER_11]: We wish.

1092
01:38:18,771 --> 01:38:21,033
[SPEAKER_05]: I guess I have a question about the Somerville one.

1093
01:38:21,053 --> 01:38:24,796
[SPEAKER_05]: If it's in a place that's kind of close to Medford.

1094
01:38:26,691 --> 01:38:35,636
[SPEAKER_05]: Is there any merit in, like, doing our own speaker series versus organizing a ride to Somerville speaker series, which already exists?

1095
01:38:35,656 --> 01:38:38,477
[SPEAKER_05]: I wonder if we have it.

1096
01:38:38,497 --> 01:38:45,180
[SPEAKER_10]: It's far enough away that people might be disinclined to go to Somerville to do it.

1097
01:38:45,260 --> 01:38:49,683
[SPEAKER_10]: I happened to go there because it was previously on the way back and forth to my office.

1098
01:38:50,695 --> 01:38:52,516
[SPEAKER_10]: And it was therefore convenient.

1099
01:38:53,497 --> 01:39:02,263
[SPEAKER_10]: Plus, you know, I'm willing to ride to Somerville, but I recognize that not everybody else is, you know, I'm sure you're willing to and probably most on the committee.

1100
01:39:02,864 --> 01:39:06,006
[SPEAKER_05]: Well, I'm really close to Somerville, but I think that's a good point.

1101
01:39:06,066 --> 01:39:09,489
[SPEAKER_05]: And that it also would be nice to support on that for business.

1102
01:39:09,729 --> 01:39:12,090
[SPEAKER_05]: If we think we have enough audience to.

1103
01:39:13,231 --> 01:39:13,792
[SPEAKER_05]: Get this going.

1104
01:39:15,183 --> 01:39:24,465
[SPEAKER_16]: It should be noted that I think it's $300 an hour bar spend minimum for private events.

1105
01:39:27,186 --> 01:39:28,686
[SPEAKER_16]: So that is something to consider.

1106
01:39:28,726 --> 01:39:42,070
[SPEAKER_16]: I don't know if they would be open to reducing that for a public or a civic event, I guess.

1107
01:39:45,620 --> 01:39:51,344
[SPEAKER_15]: This would count as a private event if it's open specifically to the public.

1108
01:39:52,325 --> 01:40:04,593
[SPEAKER_11]: It's a private event in the sense that it's taking up a bunch of space with people who are not necessarily there to buy things from the venue.

1109
01:40:06,010 --> 01:40:10,352
[SPEAKER_11]: Um, so that, that's, well, that's why they tend to have those sorts of minimums.

1110
01:40:11,732 --> 01:40:24,037
[SPEAKER_11]: Um, is because, you know, if you've got a bunch of people showing up who aren't actually going to drink, um, I've got to say that, I've got to say that, I mean, they are not just as does it as a public service, right.

1111
01:40:24,077 --> 01:40:26,498
[SPEAKER_10]: As far as I can tell, it's good.

1112
01:40:26,698 --> 01:40:28,338
[SPEAKER_10]: It's just good publicity and good.

1113
01:40:28,358 --> 01:40:29,639
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm sorry, Becca.

1114
01:40:29,659 --> 01:40:29,799
[SPEAKER_10]: What?

1115
01:40:30,706 --> 01:40:34,007
[SPEAKER_03]: I participated, I gave a talk for the Aeronaut thing.

1116
01:40:34,087 --> 01:40:41,669
[SPEAKER_03]: Aeronaut is unique in their business structure where the community part of it is actually built into their model.

1117
01:40:42,249 --> 01:40:48,311
[SPEAKER_03]: So they program that space as part of it, and I think they see themselves as not necessarily brewery, but they kind of see this other

1118
01:40:49,055 --> 01:40:50,816
[SPEAKER_03]: So I don't know if it's a private event.

1119
01:40:50,856 --> 01:40:52,676
[SPEAKER_03]: I think it's done separately.

1120
01:40:52,716 --> 01:40:59,658
[SPEAKER_03]: So that's kind of my understanding of that space is large and not the bar where you can bring beer there.

1121
01:41:00,298 --> 01:41:06,179
[SPEAKER_03]: They're not like they still have regular patrons in the space, in the regular bar area that are separate.

1122
01:41:06,199 --> 01:41:07,420
[SPEAKER_03]: They're not at the event.

1123
01:41:07,440 --> 01:41:15,002
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, there's also a couple other small businesses like a chocolate shop and at least one food place.

1124
01:41:15,622 --> 01:41:15,722
[SPEAKER_11]: Yep.

1125
01:41:16,755 --> 01:41:21,802
[SPEAKER_11]: Yeah, I mean, several visitors on Wednesday nights, but but what's the what's the question here?

1126
01:41:21,842 --> 01:41:25,247
[SPEAKER_10]: Is it is it whether we would actually pay for something?

1127
01:41:25,267 --> 01:41:28,371
[SPEAKER_10]: Is that what the how did we get into this conversation?

1128
01:41:29,452 --> 01:41:30,053
[SPEAKER_10]: I missed something.

1129
01:41:30,093 --> 01:41:30,334
[SPEAKER_10]: I think.

1130
01:41:32,768 --> 01:41:37,432
[SPEAKER_16]: It's more about whether we want to have a speaker series.

1131
01:41:38,113 --> 01:41:42,697
[SPEAKER_16]: There are multiple possible venues.

1132
01:41:42,897 --> 01:41:48,963
[SPEAKER_16]: Medford Brewing is one that was floated, but that has a possible monetary component to it.

1133
01:41:50,444 --> 01:41:53,087
[SPEAKER_16]: Another place that was floated was the library.

1134
01:41:55,141 --> 01:42:01,568
[SPEAKER_16]: So I think it's more whether we want to engage in having a speaker series.

1135
01:42:05,132 --> 01:42:10,855
[SPEAKER_15]: I feel like I might be a bit of a broken record on this sort of thing, but this could be a great idea, and it could be terrific.

1136
01:42:11,055 --> 01:42:12,496
[SPEAKER_15]: Could, not will.

1137
01:42:12,997 --> 01:42:13,497
[SPEAKER_15]: It could be.

1138
01:42:14,898 --> 01:42:23,383
[SPEAKER_15]: It's going to require someone to own it and put a fair amount of work into finding people to participate.

1139
01:42:24,103 --> 01:42:26,625
[SPEAKER_15]: We've got however many people on this call right here.

1140
01:42:27,545 --> 01:42:30,386
[SPEAKER_15]: Would everyone commit to providing a speech?

1141
01:42:30,446 --> 01:42:36,689
[SPEAKER_15]: I mean, even if, even if so, that's 13 people, seven, eight, nine of which show up regularly.

1142
01:42:36,769 --> 01:42:42,272
[SPEAKER_15]: So that's a pretty, you know, that's not a very deep bench for, you know, a monthly speaker series.

1143
01:42:42,312 --> 01:42:43,912
[SPEAKER_15]: So we would need one of us to really like.

1144
01:42:43,972 --> 01:42:48,654
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm happy to provide a speech like every six months.

1145
01:42:48,735 --> 01:42:50,795
[SPEAKER_10]: I mean, everyone would like to talk.

1146
01:42:50,835 --> 01:42:51,756
[SPEAKER_10]: So what can I say?

1147
01:42:53,745 --> 01:43:02,260
[SPEAKER_10]: And I've got a number of programs I'm willing to provide as well related to different types of bike safety and infrastructure and what they do.

1148
01:43:02,320 --> 01:43:04,144
[SPEAKER_10]: I mean, I can go on and on as you know.

1149
01:43:06,122 --> 01:43:29,528
[SPEAKER_05]: Would there be a way, I'm a little behind in my trainings of how we're allowed to operate outside this meeting, but is there a way to like, maybe if we can get two or three people to volunteer to form like a little subgroup that could, you know, update people and ask for help on a monthly basis, but work together to find people?

1150
01:43:30,488 --> 01:43:34,313
[SPEAKER_11]: Any subcommittee smaller than a quorum is acceptable, basically.

1151
01:43:34,553 --> 01:43:40,880
[SPEAKER_11]: As long as there's not a quorum, we can discuss whatever we want outside of meetings.

1152
01:43:41,140 --> 01:43:46,366
[SPEAKER_10]: As soon as there's a quorum, then it's... And of course, any decisions we make are not binding.

1153
01:43:46,786 --> 01:43:48,828
[SPEAKER_10]: We have to bring them back to the whole group for a vote.

1154
01:43:49,469 --> 01:43:51,932
[SPEAKER_10]: And, you know, that's just pro forma, typically.

1155
01:43:53,492 --> 01:44:02,437
[SPEAKER_05]: I'd be happy to, you know, I don't know that I have quite enough time or network to do it all myself, but I'd be happy to join a subcommittee.

1156
01:44:04,178 --> 01:44:08,281
[SPEAKER_16]: Do we need to motion to create a subcommittee?

1157
01:44:08,301 --> 01:44:09,161
[SPEAKER_16]: I think we do.

1158
01:44:09,682 --> 01:44:10,222
[SPEAKER_16]: So moved.

1159
01:44:10,662 --> 01:44:11,843
[SPEAKER_16]: Yes, yes, we do.

1160
01:44:11,963 --> 01:44:12,303
[SPEAKER_08]: Second.

1161
01:44:14,324 --> 01:44:14,925
[SPEAKER_16]: All in favor?

1162
01:44:16,245 --> 01:44:16,446
[SPEAKER_08]: Aye.

1163
01:44:16,826 --> 01:44:18,647
[SPEAKER_16]: All opposed?

1164
01:44:21,474 --> 01:44:26,098
[SPEAKER_16]: Okay, I guess the ayes have it.

1165
01:44:27,259 --> 01:44:31,843
[SPEAKER_10]: Who wants to be the ad hoc lead to take up organizing that committee?

1166
01:44:32,123 --> 01:44:34,145
[SPEAKER_10]: I will be willing to help on the committee.

1167
01:44:34,645 --> 01:44:39,429
[SPEAKER_10]: I don't want to be the ad hoc lead on it, but maybe Leah, you're willing to?

1168
01:44:39,449 --> 01:44:41,051
[SPEAKER_07]: Sure.

1169
01:44:48,567 --> 01:44:56,809
[SPEAKER_08]: So do we have to make a motion that she is the subcommittee chair of the ad hoc group, or is that not necessary?

1170
01:44:57,789 --> 01:45:02,830
[SPEAKER_11]: I think ad hoc groups, by definition, do not have official positions.

1171
01:45:03,530 --> 01:45:03,790
[SPEAKER_10]: Right.

1172
01:45:06,190 --> 01:45:06,310
[SPEAKER_10]: Good.

1173
01:45:06,350 --> 01:45:08,851
[SPEAKER_10]: Leah, just pick me at some point, and we'll figure out how to get this rolling.

1174
01:45:09,431 --> 01:45:09,751
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay.

1175
01:45:10,271 --> 01:45:11,791
[SPEAKER_05]: So far, it's me and Bruce.

1176
01:45:12,651 --> 01:45:13,412
[SPEAKER_05]: Oh, and Dawn.

1177
01:45:13,912 --> 01:45:14,132
[SPEAKER_07]: Yep.

1178
01:45:15,072 --> 01:45:15,412
[SPEAKER_05]: Great.

1179
01:45:16,937 --> 01:45:17,698
[SPEAKER_12]: Well, that's a group.

1180
01:45:17,958 --> 01:45:18,358
[SPEAKER_12]: All right.

1181
01:45:18,398 --> 01:45:18,899
[SPEAKER_12]: Look at that.

1182
01:45:20,060 --> 01:45:20,901
[SPEAKER_16]: Sounds good.

1183
01:45:21,761 --> 01:45:26,706
[SPEAKER_16]: I guess just so that we stay somewhat on time, and I guess this is a good segue.

1184
01:45:28,147 --> 01:45:32,691
[SPEAKER_16]: Lily, any sort of infrastructure updates?

1185
01:45:32,771 --> 01:45:38,376
[SPEAKER_16]: I'd love to hear about some of those blue bike things that you had sort of alluded to at the beginning of the meeting.

1186
01:45:40,698 --> 01:45:40,999
[SPEAKER_00]: Yes.

1187
01:45:41,579 --> 01:45:41,859
[SPEAKER_00]: So.

1188
01:45:43,184 --> 01:45:46,988
[SPEAKER_00]: We do have locations for the next 2 blue bike stations.

1189
01:45:47,188 --> 01:45:54,435
[SPEAKER_00]: There will be 1 in West Medford square, which I know is kind of been like a big kind of glaring gap and another 1.

1190
01:45:55,296 --> 01:45:57,618
[SPEAKER_00]: Which we're hoping to locate in Logan Park.

1191
01:45:58,699 --> 01:46:06,284
[SPEAKER_00]: Also, speaking of gaps, Tufts is providing 2 stations, but we still haven't gotten them to commit to a timeline.

1192
01:46:06,644 --> 01:46:17,691
[SPEAKER_00]: We're hoping it will be sometime this semester, but they've been dragging their feet a bit, but Todd is very much pushing them to keep going.

1193
01:46:17,711 --> 01:46:25,256
[SPEAKER_02]: The question on the first 2 sites, did you know if there's a timeline attached to those?

1194
01:46:26,157 --> 01:46:27,958
[SPEAKER_02]: The non-Tufts sites?

1195
01:46:29,307 --> 01:46:30,567
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, we're hoping to get them done this fall.

1196
01:46:30,587 --> 01:46:31,528
[SPEAKER_00]: Like, we don't have specific dates.

1197
01:46:31,568 --> 01:46:32,268
[SPEAKER_02]: It kind of depends on.

1198
01:46:32,308 --> 01:46:33,608
[SPEAKER_02]: We have to, like, pave a section of.

1199
01:46:45,505 --> 01:46:51,549
[SPEAKER_00]: of land, we're trying to locate these all off the street on city property so that we don't have to put them in and take them out.

1200
01:46:53,690 --> 01:47:06,037
[SPEAKER_00]: We're just trying to get them done as soon as possible, hopefully sometime in November or ideally sooner, but it's a little hard to commit to specific dates because sometimes things just get delayed and then they don't happen and then it's disappointing.

1201
01:47:06,097 --> 01:47:13,601
[SPEAKER_00]: But the location being confirmed is a big step in the process because finding good locations has been tricky.

1202
01:47:16,115 --> 01:47:24,382
[SPEAKER_08]: Might I then suggest that we reopen the question of having the infrastructure up to the task.

1203
01:47:24,422 --> 01:47:33,810
[SPEAKER_08]: If we're going to have many more bikes parked at West Medford, I think a fair number of them will want to go west and east on Route 60.

1204
01:47:34,471 --> 01:47:38,534
[SPEAKER_08]: And so I want to put a fire under our

1205
01:47:40,255 --> 01:47:48,320
[SPEAKER_08]: under the infrastructure route from West Medford Square to Mystic Valley Parkway, as we've discussed over the years.

1206
01:47:49,421 --> 01:47:50,882
[SPEAKER_08]: I think that's a great idea, Ernie.

1207
01:47:51,242 --> 01:47:53,323
[SPEAKER_10]: That probably is something we need to talk to Todd about.

1208
01:47:54,244 --> 01:47:54,464
[SPEAKER_10]: What?

1209
01:47:55,565 --> 01:47:57,466
[SPEAKER_10]: We probably need to speak to Todd about that.

1210
01:47:58,186 --> 01:48:01,469
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah, I know, but I can't see doing one without the other.

1211
01:48:03,570 --> 01:48:05,271
[SPEAKER_11]: I think that we'll get more

1212
01:48:08,663 --> 01:48:13,084
[SPEAKER_11]: Leverage on improving infrastructure if we have more bikes.

1213
01:48:13,964 --> 01:48:15,245
[SPEAKER_11]: So, if we wait.

1214
01:48:16,085 --> 01:48:19,786
[SPEAKER_11]: To do anything until we have everything we'll never do anything.

1215
01:48:22,327 --> 01:48:31,049
[SPEAKER_00]: I think at least I don't know about how Todd feels and I don't want to represent his sort of opinions, but the city's position, I think, is really to try to find.

1216
01:48:32,733 --> 01:48:45,581
[SPEAKER_00]: As many opportunities as possible to do as much as they can where they can, so I don't know where high street would come into this and how long it might take to put infrastructure there.

1217
01:48:46,442 --> 01:48:52,926
[SPEAKER_00]: I don't think it's on the immediate radar the way certain other kind of corridors are, but that doesn't mean it's not important.

1218
01:48:53,086 --> 01:48:53,286
[SPEAKER_00]: So.

1219
01:48:54,587 --> 01:49:13,193
[SPEAKER_08]: you know keeping up the advocacy and let me let me be a burdensome here and say it's just paint and signage there's no other infrastructure change it's about parking paint and signage so it can all happen within a week that's true unfortunately the way that um

1220
01:49:15,249 --> 01:49:21,752
[SPEAKER_00]: Any regulatory changes on the streets have to be approved by traffic commission and as we all know, parking is a little bit of a 3rd rail.

1221
01:49:22,292 --> 01:49:25,474
[SPEAKER_08]: I understand, but there's not a lot of money involved here.

1222
01:49:25,494 --> 01:49:28,035
[SPEAKER_08]: It's about just deciding money.

1223
01:49:28,055 --> 01:49:38,000
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, in that area, I think we've already analyzed it and it really seems like a.

1224
01:49:39,795 --> 01:49:41,156
[SPEAKER_10]: a reasonable approach.

1225
01:49:41,416 --> 01:49:47,199
[SPEAKER_10]: I mean, it's kind of like the other end of High Street where the bicycle lanes now exist.

1226
01:49:47,920 --> 01:49:54,924
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes, there was some pushback, but the reality is that the parking was so heavily underutilized that it was not a problem.

1227
01:49:55,784 --> 01:50:05,010
[SPEAKER_10]: Some people might have thought it was a problem because they had to cross the street or not be able to park directly in front of their place when somebody chose to come there, but we always get that pushback.

1228
01:50:05,945 --> 01:50:09,268
[SPEAKER_10]: And we have to make a decision one way or another that we're going to do this.

1229
01:50:09,888 --> 01:50:12,951
[SPEAKER_10]: The city's got to make that decision and live with the political ramifications.

1230
01:50:13,191 --> 01:50:13,431
[SPEAKER_10]: That's.

1231
01:50:14,532 --> 01:50:17,615
[SPEAKER_10]: You know, and our recommendation is to go in that route.

1232
01:50:17,675 --> 01:50:17,915
[SPEAKER_10]: So.

1233
01:50:18,976 --> 01:50:25,382
[SPEAKER_10]: I know, Ernie, you don't have an excellent point, but, but I also agree with you that.

1234
01:50:26,391 --> 01:50:32,016
[SPEAKER_10]: you know, if there's going to be more rent, not rental, blue bike traffic, then yeah, you're right.

1235
01:50:32,516 --> 01:50:35,699
[SPEAKER_10]: We ought to step up and have better infrastructure.

1236
01:50:36,119 --> 01:50:38,061
[SPEAKER_10]: I don't see the two having to go hand in hand.

1237
01:50:38,641 --> 01:50:39,762
[SPEAKER_10]: They won't go hand in hand.

1238
01:50:39,842 --> 01:50:42,404
[SPEAKER_10]: The blue bikes are going to go there regardless of what happens.

1239
01:50:42,444 --> 01:50:44,786
[SPEAKER_10]: So sever that notion.

1240
01:50:44,846 --> 01:50:49,950
[SPEAKER_10]: But I think it is an impetus for us to say, yeah, that becomes a high priority.

1241
01:50:50,451 --> 01:50:51,412
[SPEAKER_10]: And we really ought to look at

1242
01:50:52,429 --> 01:50:59,994
[SPEAKER_10]: Getting something complete basically between the 2 rotaries, you know, we have a good infrastructure in front of the Brooks school and up to the top of the hill.

1243
01:51:00,834 --> 01:51:03,376
[SPEAKER_10]: It'd be great to get that continued all the way to the rotary.

1244
01:51:03,396 --> 01:51:07,278
[SPEAKER_10]: And in the opposite direction, so that we have a full quarter.

1245
01:51:08,018 --> 01:51:10,340
[SPEAKER_10]: And at least on the West side of high street.

1246
01:51:13,540 --> 01:51:23,907
[SPEAKER_00]: I agree, and I think it is important to kind of, like, the more people are advocating for this, I think the higher priority it will be for the administration and the and for for Todd.

1247
01:51:24,027 --> 01:51:27,589
[SPEAKER_00]: And I will say that 1 of the things that.

1248
01:51:28,130 --> 01:51:30,491
[SPEAKER_00]: At least I've been doing more recently, and that I think.

1249
01:51:32,052 --> 01:51:42,014
[SPEAKER_00]: Um, it's trying to be elevated is actually taking parking counts and doing the kind of background data collection that will then help support making these infrastructure changes.

1250
01:51:42,054 --> 01:51:45,295
[SPEAKER_00]: So, some of the pushback from Winthrop street, um.

1251
01:51:45,915 --> 01:51:52,377
[SPEAKER_00]: Even though we know we have data saying that parking was mostly very underutilized, like, people really, you know.

1252
01:51:52,957 --> 01:52:02,741
[SPEAKER_00]: Push back against the loss of parking so when we do propose new infrastructure, we want to be able to have really strong data backing it up saying this is what we're proposing.

1253
01:52:02,801 --> 01:52:03,562
[SPEAKER_00]: We've gone out.

1254
01:52:03,882 --> 01:52:04,922
[SPEAKER_00]: We've done a lot of counts.

1255
01:52:04,982 --> 01:52:08,284
[SPEAKER_00]: We've gone at nighttime when everybody's home and asleep.

1256
01:52:08,324 --> 01:52:12,806
[SPEAKER_00]: We've gone at random times of day and during events to try to figure out how much parking is actually being used.

1257
01:52:13,266 --> 01:52:18,808
[SPEAKER_00]: So that is something we're actively pursuing on a bunch of different orders to try to lay the groundwork for some of the.

